-- China Stocks: China Vanke, Pangang Steel, Shanghai Friendship
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2011-12-27T08:18:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-27/china-stocks-china-vanke-pangang-steel-shanghai-friendship.html
Shares of the following companies
had  unusual (SHSZ300)  moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the close.  The  Shanghai Composite Index (SHCOMP) , which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, fell 1.1 percent to 2,166.21, the
lowest close since March 2009. The CSI 300 Index declined 1.3
percent to 2,305.03.  Developers:  China Vanke Co. (000002)  (000002 CH), the nation’s
biggest listed property developer, fell 2.1 percent to 7.37
yuan. Poly Real Estate Group Co. (600048 CH), the second-
largest, lost 3.2 percent to 9.76 yuan.  China Merchants Property
Development Co. (000024)  (000024 CH) retreated 2.3 percent to 17.80 yuan.  Housing transactions declined in 29 out of 35 cities
tracked by Soufun Holdings Ltd. during Dec. 19-25, according to
an e-mailed report by the country’s biggest real-estate website
owner.  Retailer stocks:  Shanghai Friendship Group Inc. (600827)  (600827
CH), an operator of department stores and supermarkets, slumped
4.2 percent to 11.50 yuan, its lowest close since Aug. 19, 2009.
Hefei Department Store Group Co. (000417 CH) dropped 2.9 percent
to 13.57 yuan.  China’s retailing industry had its recommendation cut to
“neutral” at Shenyin & Wanguo Securities Co., which said
online shopping will erode the market share of traditional
retailers, while increasing costs from rents and salaries will
hurt profitability. It didn’t say what the previous rating was.  Retailer profits may rise 18.6 percent next year and 19
percent in 2013, slowing from an estimated gain of 24.8 percent
this year, Jin Zefei, an analyst at the Shanghai-based
brokerage, wrote in a report today.  Pangang Group Steel Vanadium & Titanium Co. (000629)  (000629 CH)
jumped 6.3 percent to 5.57 yuan, its biggest gain since July 15.
The company said the securities regulator approved its asset-
swap plan with parent Angang Holding Group.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
